subsection.p:

        4x-2y \amp = 6  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Subtract 4x from both sides.}}
        -2y \amp = -4x+6  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by -2.}}
        y \amp = \dfrac{-4x}{-2}+\dfrac{6}{-2}  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Simplify.}}
        y \amp = 2x-3

The slope of the given line is ~m_1=2.  Because the unknown line is parallel to this line, its slope is also 2.  Now we know the slope of the desired line, ~m=2,  and one point on the line, (1,4). Substituting these values into the point-slope formula will give us the equation.

        y-y_1 \amp = m(x-x_1)
        y-\alert{4} \amp = \alert{2}(x-\alert{1})  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Apply the distributive law.}}
        y-4 \amp = 2x-2  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Add 4 to both sides.}}
        y \amp = 2x-2

